The Renaissance of Great Leaders
London —— The Battle of Waterloo was two centuries ago, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat there severely damaged France's self-esteem, to the extent that General Charles de Gaulle omitted it from his history of the French army.
Nevertheless, if "great" refers to a personal attribute, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle can be considered the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader."
In Marx's view, France's class struggles created the environment that made such a "freak talent" as Napoleon into a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general; his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we need to determine whether greatness can be applied to any leader.
If the answer is yes, then who among them can be considered great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did it, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "rustle of the divine mantle."
Secondly, did this leader make important decisions?
Naturally, if a leader is forced to make a decision, they cannot be blamed for it nor can they claim credit for it.
The key, therefore, lies in whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh pros and cons and make the right decision for the country.
De Gaulle should thus be on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he brought France out of the post-WWII downturn.
After returning to power in 1958, he saved his country again, suppressing two attempted coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the constitution for the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview that secured their place in the global order after World War II.
In fact, the ultimate impact of both de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their nation's worldview was perhaps too great.
Their successors continued to view the world—and their country's role in it—in ways constrained by rationality and distorted decision-making for years to come.
The result is that neither country's subsequent leaders have been able to achieve anything comparable to the feats of these two great leaders.
But there is one British prime minister who can match them: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure whom people either love or hate just as much.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to rebellions within her own cabinet and party.
A great leader does not need to please everyone.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her impact.
Besides being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom—and one of the earliest in most other countries—Thatcher helped turn around Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her offensive against too powerful unions enhanced manageability at a time when the country seemed on the verge of turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she certainly has the credentials to be considered a great leader.
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping of China also has the right to be considered a great leader.
Beyond aiding Mao Zedong in his evil deeds, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen massacre in 1989.
But Deng also liberalized the market, putting China on an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately lifted billions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many people consider Singapore's founder and longtime prime minister Lee Kuan Yew to be very great, even though he may have wished for a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country seems to have little impact on whether someone becomes a great leader.
When I said that small countries like Luxembourg are unlikely to produce great leaders, I had no insult intended, especially since the political atmosphere there is generally not controversial.
The United States, being vast, can serve as a birthplace for great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not intellectual giants — demonstrated exceptional judgment in establishing the post-war international order that supported decades of peace.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed extraordinary talents — namely, the art of rhetoric and persuasion.
John F. Kennedy could claim both qualities.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
He possessed unparalleled inspirational talent; indeed, his assassination after his death reinforced the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been deemed a great figure following Nelson Mandela's death; Mandela embodied courage, authority, and generous magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charismatic and attractive leader I have ever met; the other two – former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell – were either African or African-American.
So today?
The only one who can rightfully call herself great is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she is often underestimated at first but rarely makes mistakes when it comes to making important decisions.
Kohl devised generous terms for German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant approach to the migrant crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders – those who exercise political power – can alter circumstances, for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, guiding Europe through its high-stakes survival crises.
